</p><p>Polynomials appear in many areas of mathematics and <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Science" title=3D"Science">science</a>. For exampl=
e, they are used to form <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomia=
l_equation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Polynomial equation">polynomial =
equations</a>, which encode a wide range of problems, from elementary <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Word_problem_(mathematics_education)" t=
itle=3D"Word problem (mathematics education)">word problems</a> to complica=
ted scientific problems; they are used to define <b>polynomial functions</b=
>, which appear in settings ranging from basic <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Chemistry" title=3D"Chemistry">chemistry</a> and <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physics" title=3D"Physics">physics</a> to <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economics" title=3D"Economics">economic=
s</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_science" title=3D=
"Social science">social science</a>; and they are used in <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus" title=3D"Calculus">calculus</a> and <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numerical_analysis" title=3D"Numerical =
analysis">numerical analysis</a> to approximate other functions. In advance=
d mathematics, polynomials are used to construct <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Polynomial_ring" title=3D"Polynomial ring">polynomial rings<=
/a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_variety" title=
=3D"Algebraic variety">algebraic varieties</a>, which are central concepts =
in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebra" title=3D"Algebra">alge=
bra</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_geometry" ti=
tle=3D"Algebraic geometry">algebraic geometry</a>.
</p>
