pan></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The word <i>polynomial</i> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hybr=
id_word" title=3D"Hybrid word">joins two diverse roots</a>: the Greek <i>po=
ly</i>, meaning "many", and the Latin <i>nomen</i>, or "name". It was deriv=
ed from the term <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binomial_(poly=
nomial)" title=3D"Binomial (polynomial)">binomial</a></i> by replacing the =
Latin root <i>bi-</i> with the Greek <i>poly-</i>. That is, it means a sum =
of many terms (many <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monomial" titl=
e=3D"Monomial">monomials</a>). The word <i>polynomial</i> was first used in=
 the 17th century.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
<span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Polynomial_notation"></span>
</p>
