ynomial#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>d<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> a two-term polynomial is called a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binomial_(polynomial)" title=3D"Binomial =
(polynomial)">binomial</a>, and a three-term polynomial is called a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trinomial" title=3D"Trinomial">trinomial<=
/a>. A polynomial with two or more terms is also called a <b>multinomial</b=
>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Polynomial#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1=
3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial#cite_n=
ote-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"real_polynomial"></span><span class=3D"=
anchor" id=3D"complex_polynomial"></span><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"integ=
er_polynomial"></span>A <b>real polynomial</b> is a polynomial with <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_number" title=3D"Real number">real</=
a> coefficients. When it is used to define a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Function_(mathematics)" title=3D"Function (mathematics)">functio=
n</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Domain_(function)" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Domain (function)">domain</a> is not so restrict=
ed. However, a <b>real polynomial function</b> is a function from the reals=
 to the reals that is defined by a real polynomial. Similarly, an <b>intege=
r polynomial</b> is a polynomial with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Integer" title=3D"Integer">integer</a> coefficients, and a <b>complex p=
olynomial</b> is a polynomial with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Complex_number" title=3D"Complex number">complex</a> coefficients.
</p><p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"univariate"></span><span class=3D"ancho=
r" id=3D"bivariate"></span><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Number_of_variables=
"></span><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Multivariate_polynomial"></span>A pol=
ynomial in one indeterminate is called a <b>univariate polynomial</b>, a po=
lynomial in more than one indeterminate is called a <b>multivariate polynom=
ial</b>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A polynomial with tw=
o indeterminates is called a <b>bivariate polynomial</b>.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-:1_7-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poly=
nomial#cite_note-:1-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> These notions refer more to the kind of p=
olynomials one is generally working with than to individual polynomials; fo=
r instance, when working with univariate polynomials, one does not exclude =
constant polynomials (which may result from the subtraction of non-constant=
 polynomials), although strictly speaking, constant polynomials do not cont=
ain any indeterminates at all. It is possible to further classify multivari=
ate polynomials as <i>bivariate</i>, <i>trivariate</i>, and so on, accordin=
g to the maximum number of indeterminates allowed. Again, so that the set o=
f objects under consideration be closed under subtraction, a study of triva=
riate polynomials usually allows bivariate polynomials, and so on. It is al=
so common to say simply "polynomials in <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe=
