span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>All polynomials with coefficients in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Unique_factorization_domain" title=3D"Unique factorization domain">=
unique factorization domain</a> (for example, the integers or a <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_(mathematics)" title=3D"Field (mathemat=
ics)">field</a>) also have a factored form in which the polynomial is writt=
en as a product of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irreducible_pol=
ynomial" title=3D"Irreducible polynomial">irreducible polynomials</a> and a=
 constant. This factored form is unique up to the order of the factors and =
their multiplication by an invertible constant. In the case of the field of=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number" title=3D"Complex =
number">complex numbers</a>, the irreducible factors are linear. Over the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_number" title=3D"Real number">=
real numbers</a>, they have the degree either one or two. Over the integers=
 and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rational_number" title=3D=
"Rational number">rational numbers</a> the irreducible factors may have any=
 degree.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Barbeau-2003-pp80-82_29-0" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial#cite_note-Barbeau-2003-=
pp80-82-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> For example, the factored form of<span class=3D"mwe=
-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-displa=
y mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math display=3D"block" xm=
lns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle 5x^{3}=
-5}">
