<p>A polynomial function in one real variable can be represented by a <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_of_a_function" title=3D"Graph of =
a function">graph</a>.
</p>
<ul>
<li>
The graph of the zero polynomial
<div class=3D"block-indent"><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>x</i>) =3D =
0</span></div> is the <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i></span>-axis.
</li>
<li>
The graph of a degree 0 polynomial
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
996643573"><div class=3D"block-indent"><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>=
x</i>) =3D <i>a</i><sub>0</sub></span>, where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a<=
/i><sub>0</sub> =E2=89=A0 0</span>,</div> is a horizontal line with <span c=
lass=3D"nowrap"><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>y</i></span>-intercept <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sub>0</sub></span></span>
</li>
<li>
The graph of a degree 1 polynomial (or linear function)
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
996643573"><div class=3D"block-indent"><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>=
x</i>) =3D <i>a</i><sub>0</sub> + <i>a</i><sub>1</sub><i>x</i></span>, wher=
e <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sub>1</sub> =E2=89=A0 0</span>,</div> is=
 an oblique line with <span class=3D"nowrap"><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>y</=
i></span>-intercept <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sub>0</sub></span></sp=
an> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slope" title=3D"Slope">slo=
pe</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sub>1</sub></span>.
</li>
<li>
The graph of a degree 2 polynomial
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
996643573"><div class=3D"block-indent"><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>=
x</i>) =3D <i>a</i><sub>0</sub> + <i>a</i><sub>1</sub><i>x</i> + <i>a</i><s=
ub>2</sub><i>x</i><sup>2</sup></span>, where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</=
i><sub>2</sub> =E2=89=A0 0</span></div> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Parabola" title=3D"Parabola">parabola</a>.
</li>
<li>
The graph of a degree 3 polynomial
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
996643573"><div class=3D"block-indent"><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>=
x</i>) =3D <i>a</i><sub>0</sub> + <i>a</i><sub>1</sub><i>x</i> + <i>a</i><s=
ub>2</sub><i>x</i><sup>2</sup> + <i>a</i><sub>3</sub><i>x</i><sup>3</sup></=
span>, where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sub>3</sub> =E2=89=A0 0</span=
></div> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cubic_equation" title=
=3D"Cubic equation">cubic curve</a>.
</li>
<li>
The graph of any polynomial with degree 2 or greater
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
996643573"><div class=3D"block-indent"><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>=
x</i>) =3D <i>a</i><sub>0</sub> + <i>a</i><sub>1</sub><i>x</i> + <i>a</i><s=
ub>2</sub><i>x</i><sup>2</sup> + =E2=8B=AF + <i>a</i><sub><i>n</i></sub><i>=
x</i><sup><i>n</i></sup></span>, where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sub=
><i>n</i></sub> =E2=89=A0 0 and <i>n</i> =E2=89=A5 2</span></div> is a cont=
inuous non-linear curve.
</li>
</ul>
<p>A non-constant polynomial function <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Infinity#Calculus" title=3D"Infinity">tends to infinity</a> when the va=
riable increases indefinitely (in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Absolute_value" title=3D"Absolute value">absolute value</a>). If the degree=
 is higher than one, the graph does not have any <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Asymptote" title=3D"Asymptote">asymptote</a>. It has two <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parabolic_branch" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Parabolic branch">parabolic branches</a> with vertical directio=
n (one branch for positive <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i></span> and one =
for negative <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i></span>).
</p><p>Polynomial graphs are analyzed in calculus using intercepts, slopes,=
 concavity, and end behavior.
</p>
