</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/0c3986a6188aeb755a27bf49f2838fc06fd19881" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -0.505ex; width:17.143ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle 3=
x^{2}+4x-5=3D0}"></span>is a polynomial equation.
</p><p>When considering equations, the indeterminates (variables) of polyno=
mials are also called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variable_(ma=
thematics)" title=3D"Variable (mathematics)">unknowns</a>, and the <i>solut=
ions</i> are the possible values of the unknowns for which the equality is =
true (in general more than one solution may exist). A polynomial equation s=
tands in contrast to a <i>polynomial <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Identity_(mathematics)" title=3D"Identity (mathematics)">identity</a></i=
> like <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><=
math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle=
 (x+y)(x-y)=3Dx^{2}-y^{2}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mi>y</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <mi>y</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <msup>
          <mi>x</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <msup>
          <mi>y</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle (x+y)(x-y)=3D=
x^{2}-y^{2}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/addbb8b37188b7f10b8d3ba5e83ec0fd72e3f963" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:24.807ex; height:3.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle (x=
+y)(x-y)=3Dx^{2}-y^{2}}"></span>, where both expressions represent the same=
 polynomial in different forms, and as a consequence any evaluation of both=
 members gives a valid equality.
</p><p>In elementary <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebra" titl=
e=3D"Algebra">algebra</a>, methods such as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Quadratic_formula" title=3D"Quadratic formula">quadratic formu=
la</a> are taught for solving all first degree and second degree polynomial=
 equations in one variable. There are also formulas for the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cubic_equation" title=3D"Cubic equation">cubic</a=
> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quartic_equation" title=3D"Q=
uartic equation">quartic equations</a>. For higher degrees, the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abel%E2%80%93Ruffini_theorem" title=3D"Abel=
=E2=80=93Ruffini theorem">Abel=E2=80=93Ruffini theorem</a> asserts that the=
re can not exist a general formula in radicals. However, <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root-finding_algorithm" title=3D"Root-finding algori=
thm">root-finding algorithms</a> may be used to find <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Numerical_approximation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Numerical approximation">numerical approximations</a> of the roots of a pol=
ynomial expression of any degree.
</p><p>The number of solutions of a polynomial equation with real coefficie=
nts may not exceed the degree, and equals the degree when the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number" title=3D"Complex number">comple=
x</a> solutions are counted with their <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Multiplicity_(mathematics)" title=3D"Multiplicity (mathematics)">multi=
plicity</a>. This fact is called the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Fundamental_theorem_of_algebra" title=3D"Fundamental theorem of algebra"=
>fundamental theorem of algebra</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Solving_equations">Solving =
equations <span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Solving_polynomial_equations"></span=
></h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPolynomial=
&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit section: Solving equatio=
ns"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_equation" =
title=3D"Algebraic equation">Algebraic equation</a></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root-finding_of_polynomi=
als" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Root-finding of polynomials">Root-findi=
ng of polynomials</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Properti=
es_of_polynomial_roots" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Properties of polyno=
mial roots">Properties of polynomial roots</a></div>
<p>A <i>root</i> of a nonzero univariate polynomial <span class=3D"texhtml"=
><i>P</i></span> is a value <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-styl=
e:italic;">a</span> of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ita=
lic;">x</span> such that <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>P</i>(<i>a</i>) =3D 0</=
span>. In other words, a root of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font=
-style:italic;">P</span> is a solution of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Polynomial_equation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Polynomial =
equation">polynomial equation</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>P</i>(<i>x</i>=
) =3D 0</span> or a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zero_of_a_func=
tion" title=3D"Zero of a function">zero</a> of the polynomial function defi=
ned by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>P</i></span>. In the case of the zero pol=
ynomial, every number is a zero of the corresponding function, and the conc=
ept of root is rarely considered.
</p><p>A number <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> is a root of a poly=
nomial <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>P</i></span> if and only if the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial#linear_polynomial">linear poly=
nomial</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =E2=88=92 <i>a</i></span> divid=
es <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>P</i></span>, that is if there is another pol=
ynomial <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>Q</i></span> such that <span class=3D"te=
xhtml"><i>P</i> =3D (<i>x</i> =E2=88=92 <i>a</i>) Q</span>. It may happen t=
hat a power (greater than <span class=3D"texhtml">1</span>) of <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =E2=88=92 <i>a</i></span> divides <span class=3D"texh=
tml"><i>P</i></span>; in this case, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span>=
 is a <i>multiple root</i> of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>P</i></span>, and =
otherwise <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> is a <b>simple root</b> o=
f <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>P</i></span>. If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>P<=
/i></span> is a nonzero polynomial, there is a highest power <span class=3D=
"texhtml"><i>m</i></span> such that <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>x</i> =E2=
=88=92 <i>a</i>)<sup><i>m</i></sup></span> divides <span class=3D"texhtml">=
<i>P</i></span>, which is called the <i>multiplicity</i> of <span class=3D"=
texhtml"><i>a</i></span> as a root of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>P</i></spa=
n>. The number of roots of a nonzero polynomial <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
P</i></span>, counted with their respective multiplicities, cannot exceed t=
he degree of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>P</i></span>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-33=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial#c=
ite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> and equals this degree if all <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number" title=3D"Complex number">complex</a> r=
oots are considered (this is a consequence of the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Fundamental_theorem_of_algebra" title=3D"Fundamental theore=
m of algebra">fundamental theorem of algebra</a>).
The coefficients of a polynomial and its roots are related by <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vieta%27s_formulas" title=3D"Vieta's formulas">=
Vieta's formulas</a>.
</p><p>Some polynomials, such as <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i><sup>2</su=
p> + 1</span>, do not have any roots among the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Real_number" title=3D"Real number">real numbers</a>. If, howev=
er, the set of accepted solutions is expanded to the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number" title=3D"Complex number">complex numbers=
</a>, every non-constant polynomial has at least one root; this is the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundamental_theorem_of_algebra" title=
=3D"Fundamental theorem of algebra">fundamental theorem of algebra</a>. By =
successively dividing out factors <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =E2=88=
=92 <i>a</i></span>, one sees that any polynomial with complex coefficients=
 can be written as a constant (its leading coefficient) times a product of =
such polynomial factors of degree&nbsp;1; as a consequence, the number of (=
complex) roots counted with their multiplicities is exactly equal to the de=
gree of the polynomial.
</p><p>There may be several meanings of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Equation_solving" title=3D"Equation solving">"solving an equation"</a=
>. One may want to express the solutions as explicit numbers; for example, =
the unique solution of <span class=3D"texhtml">2<i>x</i> =E2=88=92 1 =3D 0<=
/span> is <span class=3D"texhtml">1/2</span>. This is, in general, impossib=
le for equations of degree greater than one, and, since the ancient times, =
mathematicians have searched to express the solutions as <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_expression" title=3D"Algebraic expression"=
>algebraic expressions</a>; for example, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Golden_ratio" title=3D"Golden ratio">golden ratio</a> <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml">(1+<span class=3D"nowrap">=E2=88=9A<span style=3D"border-top:=
1px solid; padding:0 0.1em;">5</span></span>)/2</span> is the unique positi=
ve solution of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i><sup>2</sup> =E2=88=92 <i>x<=
/i> =E2=88=92 1 =3D 0</span> In the ancient times, they succeeded only for =
degrees one and two. For <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic=
_equation" title=3D"Quadratic equation">quadratic equations</a>, the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_formula" title=3D"Quadratic fo=
rmula">quadratic formula</a> provides such expressions of the solutions. Si=
nce the 16th century, similar formulas (using cube roots in addition to squ=
are roots), although much more complicated, are known for equations of degr=
ee three and four (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cubic_equat=
ion" title=3D"Cubic equation">cubic equation</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Quartic_equation" title=3D"Quartic equation">quartic equ=
ation</a>). But formulas for degree 5 and higher eluded researchers for sev=
eral centuries. In 1824, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Niels_Hen=
rik_Abel" title=3D"Niels Henrik Abel">Niels Henrik Abel</a> proved the stri=
king result that there are equations of degree 5 whose solutions cannot be =
expressed by a (finite) formula, involving only arithmetic operations and r=
adicals (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abel%E2%80%93Ruffini_=
theorem" title=3D"Abel=E2=80=93Ruffini theorem">Abel=E2=80=93Ruffini theore=
m</a>). In 1830, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89variste_Gal=
ois" title=3D"=C3=89variste Galois">=C3=89variste Galois</a> proved that mo=
st equations of degree higher than four cannot be solved by radicals, and s=
howed that for each equation, one may decide whether it is solvable by radi=
cals, and, if it is, solve it. This result marked the start of <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galois_theory" title=3D"Galois theory">Galois =
theory</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Group_theory" title=
=3D"Group theory">group theory</a>, two important branches of modern <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebra" title=3D"Algebra">algebra</a>. =
Galois himself noted that the computations implied by his method were impra=
cticable. Nevertheless, formulas for solvable equations of degrees 5 and 6 =
have been published (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quintic_f=
unction" title=3D"Quintic function">quintic function</a> and <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sextic_equation" title=3D"Sextic equation">sexti=
c equation</a>).
</p><p>When there is no algebraic expression for the roots, and when such a=
n algebraic expression exists but is too complicated to be useful, the uniq=
ue way of solving it is to compute <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Numerical_approximation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Numerical approxim=
ation">numerical approximations</a> of the solutions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-34=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial#c=
ite_note-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> There are many methods for that; some are restrict=
ed to polynomials and others may apply to any <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Continuous_function" title=3D"Continuous function">continuous f=
unction</a>. The most efficient <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al=
gorithm" title=3D"Algorithm">algorithms</a> allow solving easily (on a <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer" title=3D"Computer">computer<=
/a>) polynomial equations of degree higher than 1,000 (see <i><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root-finding_algorithm" title=3D"Root-finding a=
lgorithm">Root-finding algorithm</a></i>).
</p><p>For polynomials with more than one indeterminate, the combinations o=
f values for the variables for which the polynomial function takes the valu=
e zero are generally called <i>zeros</i> instead of "roots". The study of t=
he sets of zeros of polynomials is the object of <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_geometry" title=3D"Algebraic geometry">algebraic g=
eometry</a>. For a set of polynomial equations with several unknowns, there=
 are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm" title=3D"Algorithm=
">algorithms</a> to decide whether they have a finite number of <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number" title=3D"Complex number">comp=
lex</a> solutions, and, if this number is finite, for computing the solutio=
ns. See <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/System_of_polynomial_equat=
ions" title=3D"System of polynomial equations">System of polynomial equatio=
ns</a>.
</p><p>The special case where all the polynomials are of degree one is call=
ed a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/System_of_linear_equations" t=
itle=3D"System of linear equations">system of linear equations</a>, for whi=
ch another range of different <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syst=
em_of_linear_equations#Solving_a_linear_system" title=3D"System of linear e=
quations">solution methods</a> exist, including the classical <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaussian_elimination" title=3D"Gaussian elimina=
tion">Gaussian elimination</a>.
</p><p>A polynomial equation for which one is interested only in the soluti=
ons which are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer" title=3D"In=
teger">integers</a> is called a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Di=
ophantine_equation" title=3D"Diophantine equation">Diophantine equation</a>=
. Solving Diophantine equations is generally a very hard task. It has been =
proved that there cannot be any general <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Algorithm" title=3D"Algorithm">algorithm</a> for solving them, or eve=
n for deciding whether the set of solutions is empty (see <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hilbert%27s_tenth_problem" title=3D"Hilbert's tenth=
 problem">Hilbert's tenth problem</a>). Some of the most famous problems th=
at have been solved during the last fifty years are related to Diophantine =
equations, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermat%27s_Last=
_Theorem" title=3D"Fermat's Last Theorem">Fermat's Last Theorem</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Polynomial_expressions">Pol=
ynomial expressions</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DPolynomial&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Polynomial expressions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Generalizations_of_polynomials"></span>
</p><p>Polynomials where indeterminates are substituted for some other math=
ematical objects are often considered, and sometimes have a special name.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Trigonometric_polynomials">=
Trigonometric polynomials</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DPolynomial&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit =
section: Trigonometric polynomials"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trigonometric_polyno=
mial" title=3D"Trigonometric polynomial">Trigonometric polynomial</a></div>
<p>A <b>trigonometric polynomial</b> is a finite <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Linear_combination" title=3D"Linear combination">linear comb=
ination</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Function_(mathemati=
cs)" title=3D"Function (mathematics)">functions</a> sin(<i>nx</i>) and cos(=
<i>nx</i>) with <i>n</i> taking on the values of one or more <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_number" title=3D"Natural number">natural=
 numbers</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial#cite_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The coefficient=
s may be taken as real numbers, for real-valued functions.
</p><p>If sin(<i>nx</i>) and cos(<i>nx</i>) are expanded in terms of sin(<i=
>x</i>) and cos(<i>x</i>), a trigonometric polynomial becomes a polynomial =
in the two variables sin(<i>x</i>) and cos(<i>x</i>) (using the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_trigonometric_identities#Multiple-ang=
le_formulae" title=3D"List of trigonometric identities">multiple-angle form=
ulae</a>). Conversely, every polynomial in sin(<i>x</i>) and cos(<i>x</i>) =
may be converted, with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_tri=
gonometric_identities#Product-to-sum_and_sum-to-product_identities" title=
=3D"List of trigonometric identities">Product-to-sum identities</a>, into a=
 linear combination of functions sin(<i>nx</i>) and cos(<i>nx</i>). This eq=
uivalence explains why linear combinations are called polynomials.
</p><p>For <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number" title=
=3D"Complex number">complex coefficients</a>, there is no difference betwee=
n such a function and a finite <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fou=
rier_series" title=3D"Fourier series">Fourier series</a>.
</p><p>Trigonometric polynomials are widely used, for example in <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trigonometric_interpolation" title=3D"Trigon=
ometric interpolation">trigonometric interpolation</a> applied to the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interpolation" title=3D"Interpolation">=
interpolation</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Periodic_func=
tion" title=3D"Periodic function">periodic functions</a>. They are also use=
d in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_Fourier_transfor=
m" title=3D"Discrete Fourier transform">discrete Fourier transform</a>.
</p>
