oncepts</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPoly=
nomial&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" title=3D"Edit section: Related c=
oncepts"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Rational_functions">Rationa=
l functions</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Polynomial&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D21" title=3D"Edit section: Ratio=
nal functions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rational_function" t=
itle=3D"Rational function">Rational function</a></div>
<p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rational_fraction" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Rational fraction">rational fraction</a> is the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quotient" title=3D"Quotient">quotient</a=
> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_fraction" title=3D"Al=
gebraic fraction">algebraic fraction</a>) of two polynomials. Any <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_expression" title=3D"Algebraic =
expression">algebraic expression</a> that can be rewritten as a rational fr=
action is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rational_function" tit=
le=3D"Rational function">rational function</a>.
</p><p>While polynomial functions are defined for all values of the variabl=
es, a rational function is defined only for the values of the variables for=
 which the denominator is not zero.
</p><p>The rational fractions include the Laurent polynomials, but do not l=
imit denominators to powers of an indeterminate.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Laurent_polynomials">Lauren=
t polynomials</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DPolynomial&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" title=3D"Edit section: La=
urent polynomials"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laurent_polynomial" =
title=3D"Laurent polynomial">Laurent polynomial</a></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laurent_polynomial" title=3D"La=
urent polynomial">Laurent polynomials</a> are like polynomials, but allow n=
egative powers of the variable(s) to occur.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Power_series">Power series<=
/h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPolynomial&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D23" title=3D"Edit section: Power series"><sp=
an>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></d=
iv>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formal_power_series"=
 title=3D"Formal power series">Formal power series</a></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formal_power_series" title=3D"F=
ormal power series">Formal power series</a> are like polynomials, but allow=
 infinitely many non-zero terms to occur, so that they do not have finite d=
egree. Unlike polynomials they cannot in general be explicitly and fully wr=
itten down (just like <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irrational_n=
umber" title=3D"Irrational number">irrational numbers</a> cannot), but the =
rules for manipulating their terms are the same as for polynomials. Non-for=
mal <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_series" title=3D"Power s=
eries">power series</a> also generalize polynomials, but the multiplication=
 of two power series may not converge.
</p>
