an>
So, most of the theory of the multivariate case can be reduced to an iterat=
ed univariate case.
</p><p>The map from <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>R</i></span> to <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>R</i>[<i>x</i>]</span> sending <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r=
</i></span> to itself considered as a constant polynomial is an injective <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring_homomorphism" title=3D"Ring ho=
momorphism">ring homomorphism</a>, by which <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>R</i=
></span> is viewed as a subring of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>R</i>[<i>x</i=
>]</span>. In particular, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>R</i>[<i>x</i>]</span>=
 is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebra_(ring_theory)" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Algebra (ring theory)">algebra</a> over <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml"><i>R</i></span>.
</p><p>One can think of the ring <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>R</i>[<i>x</i>]=
</span> as arising from <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>R</i></span> by adding o=
ne new element <i>x</i> to <i>R</i>, and extending in a minimal way to a ri=
ng in which <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i></span> satisfies no other rela=
tions than the obligatory ones, plus commutation with all elements of <span=
 class=3D"texhtml"><i>R</i></span> (that is <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>xr</=
i> =3D <i>rx</i></span>). To do this, one must add all powers of <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i></span> and their linear combinations as well.
</p><p>Formation of the polynomial ring, together with forming factor rings=
 by factoring out <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ideal_(ring_theo=
ry)" title=3D"Ideal (ring theory)">ideals</a>, are important tools for cons=
tructing new rings out of known ones. For instance, the ring (in fact field=
) of complex numbers, which can be constructed from the polynomial ring <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml"><i>R</i>[<i>x</i>]</span> over the real numbers by fac=
toring out the ideal of multiples of the polynomial <span class=3D"texhtml"=
><i>x</i><sup>2</sup> + 1</span>. Another example is the construction of <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finite_field" title=3D"Finite field"=
>finite fields</a>, which proceeds similarly, starting out with the field o=
f integers modulo some <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_numbe=
r" title=3D"Prime number">prime number</a> as the coefficient ring <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml"><i>R</i></span> (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Modular_arithmetic" title=3D"Modular arithmetic">modular arithmetic</a>)=
.
</p><p>If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>R</i></span> is commutative, then one =
can associate with every polynomial <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>P</i></span>=
 in <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>R</i>[<i>x</i>]</span> a <i>polynomial funct=
ion</i> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i></span> with domain and range equal=
 to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>R</i></span>.  (More generally, one can take=
 domain and range to be any same <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/U=
nital_algebra" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Unital algebra">unital</a> <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Associative_algebra" title=3D"Associ=
ative algebra">associative algebra</a> over <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>R</i=
></span>.)  One obtains the value <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>r</i>=
)</span> by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Substitution_(algebra)=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Substitution (algebra)">substitution</a> o=
f the value <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i></span> for the symbol <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i></span> in <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>P</i></span>.=
 One reason to distinguish between polynomials and polynomial functions is =
that, over some rings, different polynomials may give rise to the same poly=
nomial function (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermat%27s_li=
ttle_theorem" title=3D"Fermat's little theorem">Fermat's little theorem</a>=
 for an example where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>R</i></span> is the intege=
rs modulo <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>p</i></span>). This is not the case wh=
en <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>R</i></span> is the real or complex numbers, =
whence the two concepts are not always distinguished in <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analysis_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Analysis (mathematics)">analysis</a>. An even more important reason to =
distinguish between polynomials and polynomial functions is that many opera=
tions on polynomials (like <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclide=
an_division" title=3D"Euclidean division">Euclidean division</a>) require l=
ooking at what a polynomial is composed of as an expression rather than eva=
luating it at some constant value for <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i></spa=
n>.
</p>
