le=3D"Euclidean domain">Euclidean domain</a>.
</p><p>Analogously, <i>prime polynomials</i> (more correctly, <i><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irreducible_polynomial" title=3D"Irreducible=
 polynomial">irreducible polynomials</a></i>) can be defined as <i>non-zero=
 polynomials which cannot be factorized into the product of two non-constan=
t polynomials</i>. In the case of coefficients in a ring, <i>"non-constant"=
</i> must be replaced by <i>"non-constant or non-<a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Unit_(ring_theory)" title=3D"Unit (ring theory)">unit</a>"</=
i> (both definitions agree in the case of coefficients in a field). Any pol=
ynomial may be decomposed into the product of an invertible constant by a p=
roduct of irreducible polynomials. If the coefficients belong to a field or=
 a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unique_factorization_domain" ti=
tle=3D"Unique factorization domain">unique factorization domain</a> this de=
composition is unique up to the order of the factors and the multiplication=
 of any non-unit factor by a unit (and division of the unit factor by the s=
ame unit). When the coefficients belong to integers, rational numbers or a =
finite field, there are algorithms to test irreducibility and to compute th=
e factorization into irreducible polynomials (see <i><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Factorization_of_polynomials" title=3D"Factorization of =
polynomials">Factorization of polynomials</a></i>). These algorithms are no=
t practicable for hand-written computation, but are available in any <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_algebra_system" title=3D"Comput=
er algebra system">computer algebra system</a>. <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Eisenstein%27s_criterion" title=3D"Eisenstein's criterion">Ei=
senstein's criterion</a> can also be used in some cases to determine irredu=
cibility.
</p>
