</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Interpolation_and_approxima=
tion">Interpolation and approximation</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/w/index.php?title=3DPolynomial&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D28" ti=
tle=3D"Edit section: Interpolation and approximation"><span>edit</span></a>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial_interpolation=
" title=3D"Polynomial interpolation">Polynomial interpolation</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthogonal_polynomials" title=3D"Orthogon=
al polynomials">Orthogonal polynomials</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/B-spline" title=3D"B-spline">B-spline</a>, and <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spline_interpolation" title=3D"Spline interpolation"=
>spline interpolation</a></div>
<p>The simple structure of polynomial functions makes them quite useful in =
analyzing general functions using polynomial approximations. An important e=
xample in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus" title=3D"Calcu=
lus">calculus</a> is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taylor%27s_th=
eorem" title=3D"Taylor's theorem">Taylor's theorem</a>, which roughly state=
s that every <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differentiable_functi=
on" title=3D"Differentiable function">differentiable function</a> locally l=
ooks like a polynomial function, and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Stone%E2%80%93Weierstrass_theorem" title=3D"Stone=E2=80=93Weierstras=
s theorem">Stone=E2=80=93Weierstrass theorem</a>, which states that every <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuous_function" title=3D"Conti=
nuous function">continuous function</a> defined on a <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Compact_space" title=3D"Compact space">compact</a> <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interval_(mathematics)" title=3D"Interv=
al (mathematics)">interval</a> of the real axis can be approximated on the =
whole interval as closely as desired by a polynomial function.  Practical m=
ethods of approximation include <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Po=
lynomial_interpolation" title=3D"Polynomial interpolation">polynomial inter=
polation</a> and the use of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spline=
_(mathematics)" title=3D"Spline (mathematics)">splines</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-41" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polyno=
mial#cite_note-41"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Other_applications">Other a=
pplications</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Polynomial&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D29" title=3D"Edit section: Other=
 applications"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<p>Polynomials are frequently used to encode information about some other o=
bject. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Characteristic_polynomi=
al" title=3D"Characteristic polynomial">characteristic polynomial</a> of a =
matrix or linear operator contains information about the operator's <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalue" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Eigenvalue">eigenvalues</a>. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Minimal_polynomial_(field_theory)" title=3D"Minimal polynomial (field th=
eory)">minimal polynomial</a> of an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Algebraic_element" title=3D"Algebraic element">algebraic element</a> reco=
rds the simplest algebraic relation satisfied by that element. The <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chromatic_polynomial" title=3D"Chromatic =
polynomial">chromatic polynomial</a> of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Graph_(discrete_mathematics)" title=3D"Graph (discrete mathematics)=
">graph</a> counts the number of proper colourings of that graph.
</p><p>The term "polynomial", as an adjective, can also be used for quantit=
ies or functions that can be written in polynomial form. For example, in <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computational_complexity_theory" tit=
le=3D"Computational complexity theory">computational complexity theory</a> =
the phrase <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial_time" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Polynomial time">polynomial time</a></i> means =
that the time it takes to complete an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Algorithm" title=3D"Algorithm">algorithm</a> is bounded by a polynomial=
 function of some variable, such as the size of the input.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPolynomial&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D30" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cubic_function#Hist=
ory" title=3D"Cubic function">Cubic function =C2=A7&nbsp;History</a>, <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quartic_function#History" title=3D"Quar=
tic function">Quartic function =C2=A7&nbsp;History</a>, and <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abel%E2%80%93Ruffini_theorem#History" title=3D"Ab=
el=E2=80=93Ruffini theorem">Abel=E2=80=93Ruffini theorem =C2=A7&nbsp;Histor=
y</a></div>
<p>Determining the roots of polynomials, or "solving algebraic equations", =
is among the oldest problems in mathematics. However, the elegant and pract=
ical notation we use today only developed beginning in the 15th century. Be=
fore that, equations were written out in words. For example, an algebra pro=
blem from the Chinese <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Nine_Cha=
pters_on_the_Mathematical_Art" title=3D"The Nine Chapters on the Mathematic=
al Art">Arithmetic in Nine Sections</a>, <abbr title=3D"circa">c.</abbr><sp=
an style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=89200&nbsp;BCE</span>, begins "Thre=
e sheafs of good crop, two sheafs of mediocre crop, and one sheaf of bad cr=
op are sold for 29 dou." We would write <span class=3D"texhtml">3<i>x</i> +=
 2<i>y</i> + <i>z</i> =3D 29</span>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"History_of_the_notation">Hi=
story of the notation</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DPolynomial&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D31" title=3D"Edit sect=
ion: History of the notation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_mathemati=
cal_notation" title=3D"History of mathematical notation">History of mathema=
tical notation</a></div>
<p>The earliest known use of the equal sign is in <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Recorde" title=3D"Robert Recorde">Robert Recorde</a>=
's <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Whetstone_of_Witte" titl=
e=3D"The Whetstone of Witte">The Whetstone of Witte</a></i>, 1557. The sign=
s + for addition, =E2=88=92 for subtraction, and the use of a letter for an=
 unknown appear in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Stifel"=
 title=3D"Michael Stifel">Michael Stifel</a>'s <i>Arithemetica integra</i>,=
 1544. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ren%C3%A9_Descartes" title=
=3D"Ren=C3=A9 Descartes">Ren=C3=A9 Descartes</a>, in <i>La g=C3=A9ometrie</=
i>, 1637, introduced the concept of the graph of a polynomial equation. He =
popularized the use of letters from the beginning of the alphabet to denote=
 constants and letters from the end of the alphabet to denote variables, as=
 can be seen above, in the general formula for a polynomial in one variable=
, where the <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span>s denote constants and <=
span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i></span> denotes a variable. Descartes introd=
uced the use of superscripts to denote exponents as well.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-42" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomi=
al#cite_note-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
